AmaXhosa King Mpendulo Zwelonke Sigcawu (51) has been buried atÂ Nqadu Great Place, Willowvale in the Eastern. He died two weeks ago at Nelson Mandela Academy Hospital.  King Zwwlonke grew up in the small town of Cofimvamba.  People came in large numbers to bid a last farewell AmaXhosa King Zwelonke Sigcawu. Royal families, politi2cians, church leaders across the country came to say good-byes to AmaXhosa King. South African president Cyril Ramaphosa, former president Thabo Mbeki, Julies Malema, and others were among the people who attended the funeral service. King Zwelonke Sigcawu has been honoured with a state funeral category one. Nkosi Zolile Ncamashe said the nation has lost a hero who loved his country.  "He was very proud about his language. He was the person who was very love and respect his language. "In these days you will hear people speaking English but both of them are Xhosas. But King Zwelonke was the person that you would not hear him doing that. He leaves at the time we are busy trying to bring the dignity of the nation," he said.  Former President Thabo Mbeki said AmaXhosa Zwelonke Sigcawu lives at the time people of South Africa are facing the shortage of water.  "We ask King Zwelonke to ask God to provide us by rain. I want to thank our president Cyril Ramaphosa for honouring AmaXhosa King Zwelonke Sigcawu with state funeral. King Zwelonke was very vocal about xenophobia. He died while we were arranging to meet. I regret that day because it did not arrive because he passed on. He was such a leader that is why we are here today to pay tribute to him," said Mbeki.  South African President Cyril Ramaphosa said he want to thank local government of the Eastern Cape for requesting state funeral. "As the nation we lost great leader who was the pillar of his community.